$ Shell command: useradd
@ useradd

Create a new → Linux/user[user] or update default new user information.

It is a *low level utility*. Therefore, you might want to use → Linux/shell/commands/adduser.

Use the `-m` flag to create the new user's → Linux/home-directory if it does not exist.

If not invoked with `-s` to specify the shell, it assumes the value of `SHELL` variable in → Linux/fhs/etc/default/useradd.

If not invoked with `-k`, the files from the `SKEL` variable in → Linux/fhs/etc/default/useradd (default: →Linux/fhs/etc/skel[/etc/skel/*]) are copied into the new user's home directory.

A user is removed/deleted with →Linux/shell/commands/userdel.

code {
useradd -m rene
passwd rene
code }

sa:

  → Linux/shell/commands/groupadd

  → Linux/shell/commands/passwd 

  → Linux/shell/commands/index[Shell commands]

